comments.content:
@eliason - I've increased the letterspacing and it definitely looks better. Thanks.

@riccard0 - I agree with the /x/ weight - I'll take a look at that today. As for the top-right curve, this is something I've already started experimenting with, not just on the /x/, but also on the /v/, /w/ and /y/. I originally designed these glyphs with a curve because the standard form looked horribly plain in context. The same was true of the /z/, which I dealt with by adding a kink around 1/3 of way down.

I hadn't considered an alternative form the the /g/, but I really like the idea of trying an open bowl.

@Vladimir - the alley remains unfamiliar, but it's reassuring to have such good company! :)

@Catharsis - since my last update, I've been experimenting with the possibility of turning this into a serif font, using the /f/ crossbar as a template for the serifs. I've linked to a very rough implementation to test the concept - I've not taken the time to ensure everything lines up properly and I am aware some of the serifs widths will need adjusting, but do you think this is likely to result in a better font?

[http://freepdfhosting.com/a76d7ca427.pdf](http://web.archive.org/web/20150404082217/http:/freepdfhosting.com/a76d7ca427.pdf "http://freepdfhosting.com/a76d7ca427.pdf")

Once I'm clear about the direction it will take, I'll address the most recent points you've made.

@riccard0 - hehe, they are funky, aren't they? :)

If I can get the underlying letterforms right, I'll create a serif variation.

@Catharsis - I agree with most of what you said. I don't like the n-like ascender tops either, and I need to revisit the way the flare works.

I take your point about the /z/, and I will try alternatives, but I actually quite like it the way it is.

As for the /g/, I will lighten the eye, but do you really think the ruggedness of this letter is out-of-place? It is more rugged than most, for sure, but isn't that down to it's meandering nature more than execution? If I smooth it out, won't I be retreating from the calligraphic style I've been working towards? That said, I'll play around with it and see where it takes me.

Lastly, for now, you wondered how the /a/ and /z/ would look without the serifs. You can get a reasonable approximation by looking at my original PDF ( [http://freepdfhosting.com/e290ad9e0c.pdf](http://web.archive.org/web/20150404082217/http:/freepdfhosting.com/e290ad9e0c.pdf "http://freepdfhosting.com/e290ad9e0c.pdf")). Do you think they work better?

@eliason

I misunderstood. I thought you meant both that the junction was too low AND that it had an unbalanced (left/right) appearance. Re-reading your comment again, it is clear you were talking only about the junction.

In the event, I raised the junction to give the stem a chance to straighten a little and left-shifted the arms. I think the current one is all-round better than it was, but maybe not quite right?
